 :experiment/verdict
 "THINKING-OFF is the cross-model exhaustion fix; the max_tokens cap FAILS and HARMS qwen (2026-07-17, :local qwen36-35b-a3b + :gemma4 gemma-4-31b-it, bounded lens, 24 cells). H1 (lens prose) already falsified; H2 settles the operational lever.\n  THE MECHANISM (the load-bearing finding): gemma4 exhaustion is WALL-CLOCK-bound, NOT token-bound. gemma4 capped :max-tokens 3072 think-ON STILL exhausts on both dense turns (243.5s wall) — its slow reasoning pass never reaches 3072 tokens within the ask budget, so the token cap never bites. Only REMOVING the reasoning pass escapes the wall.\n  LEVER RESULTS:\n    thinking-OFF (uncapped): gemma4 3/3 VALID avg 15.9s/241tok · local 3/3 VALID avg 2.6s/181tok — BOTH families, ALL turns incl. the 2 that exhausted under think-ON, value-survival (:keeps?) intact (runtime-arch keeps escapement/statechart/scorer/curator; compression-stats keeps 57.9×/66.9×/117.7×). THE FIX.\n    thinking-ON (uncapped): gemma4 1/3 (2 dense EXHAUST, 169s avg) · local 3/3 VALID but slow/verbose (39s, 4424tok). Baseline reproduced.\n    :max-tokens 3072 + thinking-ON: gemma4 STILL 1/3 (cap useless — wall-clock fires first) · local parse 1/3 (cap TRUNCATES: reasoning eats 3072 before the answer, 2/3 lost). The cap is STRICTLY BAD with thinking-on.\n  COST BONUS: think-OFF is 10× cheaper AND faster — gemma4 15.9s vs 169s(+exhaust), local 2.6s vs 39s; fits the 20-60s reading shadow with room on BOTH models (think-ON gemma4 dense turns blow it 4× over).\n  HONEST LIMIT: the :lambda-compaction measure is a decidable FLOOR (¬echo ∧ shorter ∧ keeps), NOT semantic quality — the reason thinking-ON was originally KEPT (🎯 human-settled, on qwen single-family). So this proves think-OFF produces a VALID faithful-floor compaction where think-ON produces NOTHING; it does NOT prove think-OFF matches think-ON semantic quality on normal turns. A quality re-test (compaction-continuity / a judge) is required before adopting think-OFF generally.\n  CONSEQUENCE (production, human-gated — reopens a human-settled policy): options —\n    (a) ADAPTIVE FALLBACK: compaction runs think-ON; on exhaust/soft-time-budget, retry think-OFF. Keeps think-ON quality on normal turns, GUARANTEES output on dense/slow ones. Most machinery, best behavior.\n    (b) PER-MODEL: slow-thinking models (gemma4) compact think-OFF, fast (qwen) keep think-ON. Simple, bifurcates.\n    (c) THINK-OFF GENERALLY: simplest, cheapest, cross-model-robust — but reopens the settled quality decision; gate on a quality re-test.\n  The :max-tokens infra knob (λ extend) earned its keep by RULING OUT the cap empirically and is reusable; it is NOT the compaction fix.",
 :experiment/hypothesis
 "H2 — the CROSS-MODEL exhaustion is OPERATIONAL, fixable by a knob not lens prose (H1 falsified). gemma4 exhausts on dense multi-entity turns (runtime-arch, compression-stats) at the ~240s ask wall because its uncapped thinking pass never converges; qwen completes (terse reasoning). Two operational levers, both first-class escapement modeled fields flowing through the REAL ellm/ask path (experiment infra extended for them, λ extend): (1) :max-tokens cap — bounds total generation (reasoning+content) so a slow reasoner is forced to stop; (2) thinking-OFF (matrix axis) — removes the reasoning pass entirely. Bounded lens (the quality winner from compaction-lens-bounded). Subjects: the 2 exhausting dense turns + writeback control (must not regress the easy turn). FALSIFIER: neither lever makes gemma4 converge on the dense turns with value-survival intact. WIN: a lever drives gemma4 exhaustion→0 while keeping :keeps? on both families. Reads what a cross-model production compactor must set.",
