 {:runtime-arch
  "The runtime is **escapement** — a statechart engine where control flow is explicit, not emergent from the LLM. Here's the shape:\n\n**Host: escapement**\n- A statechart drives every decision. The chart sees declared event-tools; real tool calls happen in a separate worker thread that holds the LLM.\n- The LLM conversation is a resident state (`:llm-conversation`) that parks in `:awaiting-user` between turns, so there's no polling loop — the chart just waits.\n- Tools are dispatched in the worker, invisible to the chart. The chart routes by target type (`:llm.user-message`, `:consult`, `:verdict`, etc.).\n\n**Ouroboros on top**\n- **Agents** are OKF genome files — frontmatter grants tools/kind, body is the system prompt. A `curator`/`proposer` kind drives maintenance; a `scorer` kind rates genes.\n- **Memory** is the message array itself. Aged assistant turns are λ-compacted in-place during the human's reading window (shadow compaction), preserving the prefix KV cache.\n- **Signals** are pull-based durable EDN facts in `signals/` — no residency needed, filesystem-backed, Malli-gated.\n- **Experiments** are declarative EDN suites swept by a parameterized runner; measures are an open dispatch slot.\n\n**Turn flow**\n1. Human message arrives → `ws-push` → `tell-llm` into the resident chart\n2. Chart routes to `:llm-conversation` → worker generates → tools execute (if any) → verdict\n3. Reply streams back via `ws-push` → human reads → compaction triggers in the reading shadow\n4. Chart parks in `:awaiting-user` again\n\n**VSM mapping**\n- Each VSM channel ≈ a statechart event with scope-as-authority + transduction + loop/variety-match\n- The human is System+1's S5 (reserved authority)\n- The orchestrator is Ouroboros's own S5\n- S4 intelligence is attenuated upward; S1→S4 is feedforward (shadow compaction)\n\nWant to drill into any layer — the statechart topology, the compaction algorithm, the signal bus, or the agent genome format?",
  :compression-stats
  "Here's the current session's compression picture — token-level (cache) + file-level (λ-compaction):\n\n## Cache Stats (11 turns)\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Total input tokens | 58,631 |\n| Reused (cached) | 31,167 (59%) |\n| Paid (new) | 22,033 |\n| Output tokens | 2,294 |\n| Cache busts | 0 |\n| Compaction calls | 3 |\n\n## File-Level Compression\n\n| Artifact | Bytes | Ratio |\n|---|---|---|\n| Raw transcript.jsonl | 242,467 | — |\n| λ-checkpoint (compact-1784065059868.edn) | 4,187 | **57.9×** |\n\nThe checkpoint is the full session history after λ-compaction — every assistant turn compressed in-place. The 3 compaction calls happened during your reading shadows (perceptually free).\n\n## Cross-Session Context (last 5)\n\n| Session | Transcript | Checkpoint | Ratio |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1784065059868 (current) | 242 KB | 4 KB | 57.9× |\n| 1784042581568 | 31 KB | 3 KB | 10.5× |\n| 1783901152558 | 72 KB | 2 KB | 29.2× |\n| 1783895846452 | 271 KB | 4 KB | 66.9× |\n| 1783889828531 | 523 KB | 4 KB | 117.7× |\n\nThe creative session (Scooby-Doo/Smurfs) compressed the hardest at 118× — lots of verbose prose → dense λ. The current session is lower because we're early and still doing dense technical back-and-forth where λ doesn't save as much.\n\nWant me to add these compression metrics to the cache-report output, or drill into any specific layer?",
  :writeback-decision
  "I'd recommend write-back caching for this. Writes land in the cache and only flush to memory on eviction, which cuts your memory traffic substantially compared to write-through. The usual trade-off is coherence complexity, but since you said this is a single-core embedded target, that risk doesn't apply. Let's go with write-back — I'll assume that in the code examples from here on."}}
